s Huron phrasebook, published in 1632, and the sophisticated Jesuit missionary study of the language from the 1620s to the 1740s, beginning with the work of Father Jean de Brébeuf. The only book of its kind, Words of the Huron will spark discussion among scholars, students, and anyone interested in North American archaeology, Native studies, cultural anthropology, and seventeenth-century North American history.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aNames, WyandotxHistoryy17th century. 0aWyandot IndiansxIntellectual lifey17th century. 0aWyandot IndiansxLanguagesxHistoryy17th century. 0aWyandot IndiansxMaterial culturexHistoryy17th century. 0aWyandot IndiansxReligion. 0aWyandot IndiansxSocial life and customsy17th century. 0aWyandot languagexHistory. 4aHistory: Canadian History. 4aIndigenous Studies. 7aHISTORY / Native American.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package Pre-2010z978311127416408iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package pre 2010z978311127724040uhttps://doi.org/10.51644/978155458135140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781554581351423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781554581351/original  a978-3-11-127416-4  ACUP Complete eBook-Package Pre-2010b2010  a978-3-11-127724-0  ACUP Upgrade eBook-Package pre 2010b2010  aGBV-deGruyter-alles